# ScrapCo V2 — Phased Roadmap

## 1. Roadmap Philosophy

ScrapCo V2 must be built in controlled, production-safe phases.

Rules:

- Do not build everything at once.
- Core dispatch stability first.
- Marketplace mechanics second.
- Financial complexity later.
- Scale only after stability.
- Never compromise architecture for speed.

Each phase must be deployable and usable independently.

---

## 2. Phase 0 — Foundation (Architecture Freeze)

Objective:
Lock architecture, schema, and infrastructure before feature expansion.

Deliverables:

- Monorepo setup (web, mobile, api, worker)
- Environment validation system
- Database schema implemented
- Redis + BullMQ configured
- CI pipeline functional
- Health endpoints implemented
- Logging & error tracking integrated
- Role-based auth middleware implemented
- Rate limiting + Helmet + CORS configured

Exit Criteria:

- API deployable
- Worker deployable
- No in-memory dispatch
- No env-toggle admin
- Health checks passing
- CI passing

No marketplace logic yet.

---

## 3. Phase 1 — Core Marketplace (Sequential Model)

Objective:
Stable dispatch with sequential vendor offer model.

Deliverables:

- Seller pickup creation
- Dispatch job queue
- Vendor selection logic
- Offer creation + expiry
- Vendor accept/reject
- Assignment creation
- Pickup lifecycle transitions
- Audit logging
- Real-time updates (no polling)
- Seller dashboard (basic)
- Vendor dashboard (basic)
- Admin scrap type + scrap rate management

Operational Constraints:

- Single region tested first
- Commission stored per transaction
- Basic transaction record creation
- Rating submission

Exit Criteria:

- Assignment success rate measurable
- Assignment time < 5 minutes (P95)
- No duplicate assignments
- No lost dispatch jobs
- No critical security gaps
- System stable in 3 cities

This phase makes ScrapCo operational.

---

## 4. Phase 2 — Marketplace Enhancement

Objective:
Introduce vendor competition and operational intelligence.

Deliverables:

- Parallel vendor offer support
- First-accept wins model
- Vendor capacity tracking
- Vendor availability toggle
- Vendor acceptance rate metrics
- Commission configuration per region
- Basic vendor earnings dashboard
- Queue performance tuning
- Admin region-level analytics
- Rate limiting optimization
- Performance optimizations (index tuning)

Optional Additions:

- Wallet table implementation
- Vendor performance ranking refinement

Exit Criteria:

- Vendor competition functional
- Capacity-aware dispatch
- Real-time reliability under load
- Dispatch success rate improved
- Worker horizontally scalable

This phase strengthens marketplace dynamics.

---

## 5. Phase 3 — Financial Layer

Objective:
Introduce structured financial management.

Deliverables:

- Wallet system activated
- Commission settlement tracking
- Transaction adjustment system
- Refund handling support
- Payment gateway integration (optional)
- Earnings statement export
- Commission reporting per region
- Fraud flagging logic

Constraints:

- No deletion of financial records
- Immutable transaction logs
- Commission configurable without code change

Exit Criteria:

- Financial records auditable
- Wallet balances accurate
- Revenue dashboard operational
- Commission revenue measurable

This phase enables monetization scale.

---

## 6. Phase 4 — Operational Scaling

Objective:
Prepare for 10+ cities expansion.

Deliverables:

- Region onboarding tooling
- Vendor onboarding automation
- Vendor verification workflow
- Region-level SLA tracking
- Queue scaling improvements
- Redis performance tuning
- DB performance tuning
- Deployment auto-scaling
- Production monitoring alerts refined

Operational Requirements:

- Region addition requires no code change
- Scaling does not break dispatch
- Horizontal API scaling tested

Exit Criteria:

- Multi-city performance stable
- Dispatch resilient to high concurrency
- Monitoring actionable

This phase prepares national scaling.

---

## 7. Phase 5 — Advanced Marketplace Evolution

Objective:
Build network-level advantages.

Deliverables:

- Recycler integration
- Multi-tier marketplace logic
- Dynamic pricing engine
- Smart vendor ranking algorithm
- AI-based dispatch optimization
- Analytics dashboard for growth
- Demand-supply heatmap
- SLA optimization tools

Optional:

- Subscription-based vendor tiers
- Featured placement model
- Premium seller services

This phase transforms ScrapCo into infrastructure.

---

## 8. What NOT to Build Early

Avoid in early phases:

- Full wallet microservice
- Microservices architecture
- AI pricing engine
- Heavy analytics dashboards
- Blockchain-based ideas
- Chat systems
- Complex social features

Focus on:

- Stable dispatch
- Secure system
- Reliable real-time
- Measurable performance

---

## 9. Phase Prioritization Strategy

Build Order:

1. Backend Core + Dispatch Engine
2. Web Seller Dashboard
3. Vendor Dashboard
4. Real-time System
5. Security Hardening
6. Observability
7. Competition Model
8. Financial Layer

Never reverse this order.

---

## 10. Technical Debt Policy

If during any phase:

- Dispatch becomes unstable
- Security gap discovered
- Real-time unreliable
- Assignment logic inconsistent

Stop feature development.
Fix core system first.

---

## 11. Scaling Strategy Timeline

City Expansion Plan:

Phase 1:
- Narnaul

Phase 2:
- Gorakhpur
- Singhana

Phase 3:
- 5 additional cities

Phase 4:
- 10+ cities

Each expansion must:

- Measure dispatch metrics
- Validate vendor density
- Validate acceptance rate

No blind expansion.

---

## 12. Success Milestones

Phase 1 Success:

- Stable operations in 3 cities
- Vendor acceptance > 60%
- Assignment time < 5 minutes

Phase 2 Success:

- Vendor competition functional
- Capacity-aware dispatch

Phase 3 Success:

- Commission revenue predictable
- Wallet reconciliation accurate

Phase 4 Success:

- Horizontal scaling proven
- Multi-city operations stable

---

## 13. Long-Term Objective

ScrapCo must evolve into:

- Structured scrap marketplace infrastructure
- Region-scalable logistics network
- Commission-based revenue engine
- Data-driven optimization platform

Roadmap ensures this happens without architectural rewrite.

---

## 14. Summary

ScrapCo V2 roadmap ensures:

- Stability before scale
- Architecture before features
- Security before expansion
- Observability before automation
- Marketplace mechanics before financial complexity

No shortcuts.

Each phase builds on stable foundation.
```
